# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: annette-faße
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 27 September 2009 to elect the members of the 17th Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU), its Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social Union (CSU), and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) won the election, and the three parties formed a new centre-right government with Angela Merkel as chancellor.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] While CDU/CSU's share of votes decreased slightly, it was more than compensated by the gains of their "desired coalition partner", the liberal FDP, that won the strongest result in its history.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] CDU and CSU's former partner in the "Grand coalition", the Social Democratic Party (SPD) led by Frank-Walter Steinmeier, conceded defeat after dropping by more than 11 percentage points, receiving its hitherto worst result since the end of the Second World War (only undercut in 2017 and 2025).
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] At 70.8 percent, the voter turnout was the lowest in a German federal election since 1949.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] According to Article 38 of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany, members of the Bundestag shall be elected in general, direct, free, equal, and secret elections; everyone over the age of eighteen is entitled to vote.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] In 2008, some modifications to the electoral system were required under an order of the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The court had found a provision in the Federal Election Law by which it was possible for a party to experience a negative vote weight, namely losing seats due to more votes, violated the constitutional guarantee of the electoral system being equal and direct.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The court allowed three years for these changes, so the 2009 German federal election was not affected.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The changes were due by 30 June 2011 but appropriate legislation was not completed by that deadline.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] A new electoral law was enacted in late 2011 but was declared unconstitutional once again by the Federal Constitutional Court upon lawsuits from the opposition parties and a group of some 4,000 private citizens.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag approved and enacted the new electoral reform in February 2013.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag is elected using mixed-member proportional representation, meaning that each voter has two votes, a first vote for the election of a constituency candidate by first-past-the-post and a second vote for the election of a state list.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method is used to convert the votes into seats, in a two-stage process with each stage involving two calculations.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] First, the number of seats to be allocated to each state is calculated, based on the proportion of the German population living there.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Then the seats in each state are allocated to the party lists in that state, based on the proportion of second votes each party received.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] In the distribution of seats among state lists, only parties that have obtained at least five percent of the valid second votes cast in the electoral area or have won a seat in at least three constituencies are taken into consideration.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The minimum number of seats for each party at federal level is then determined.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] This is done by calculating, for each party state list, the number of constituency seats it won on the basis of the first votes, as well as the number of seats to which it is entitled on the basis of the second votes.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The higher of these two figures is the party's minimum number of seats in that state.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Adding together the minimum number of seats to which the party is entitled in all of the states produces a total representing its guaranteed minimum number of seats in the country as a whole.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] In order to ensure that each party receives its guaranteed minimum number of seats when the seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method, it may become necessary to increase the number of seats in the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Then it must be ensured that the seats are distributed to the parties in line with their national share of the second votes.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Additional overhang seats, or balance seats, are created to ensure that the distribution of the seats reflects the parties' share of the second votes and that no party receives fewer than its guaranteed minimum number of seats.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Balance seats are also necessary to ensure that each party requires roughly the same number of second votes per seat.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Once the number of seats which each party is entitled to receive across the country has been determined, the seats are allocated to the parties' individual state lists.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Each state list must receive at least as many seats as the number of constituencies which the party won in the state in question.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Since the 2005 election, Chancellor Angela Merkel (CDU) had governed in a grand coalition with the SPD.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] However, it was her stated goal to win a majority for CDU/CSU and FDP (the CDU/CSU's traditional coalition partner) in 2009.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Foreign minister and Vice-Chancellor Frank-Walter Steinmeier (SPD) was formally nominated as his party's chancellor-candidate at a convention on 18 October 2008.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] He aimed to form a government in which the SPD was the strongest party, but which also excluded the left-socialist party The Left.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The election campaign was considered exceptionally boring, which may be attributable to a perceived lack of charisma on the part of the leaders of the CDU and SPD.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Another reason pointed to for the sedate campaign is that the CDU and SPD both defended the record of their grand coalition, and facing the possibility of having to continue the grand coalition in a friendly manner.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Merkel was content with the low-key campaign style, which was largely seen as benefiting her party because of her high approval ratings.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] CDU candidate Vera Lengsfeld released a campaign poster featuring herself and Merkel in a way that emphasised their cleavage.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The poster bore the slogan "We have more to offer" (German: "*Wir haben mehr zu bieten*").
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] On 23 September 2009, four days before the federal elections, German police raided the Berlin headquarters of the National Democratic Party of Germany NPD to investigate claims that letters sent from the NPD to politicians from immigrant backgrounds incited racial hatred.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The federal election was the final and most important election in what is called a *Superwahljahr* (super election year) in Germany.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU and FDP, with an average vote share of around 50% in pre-election polling during the weeks before the election, were clearly ahead of the other traditional coalition partners in Germany, SPD and the Greens.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU received a slightly lower proportion than in the previous election, with the Bavarian CSU receiving its lowest vote share in decades.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Overall, the CDU/CSU had their worst vote share in 60 years.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] In contrast, their preferred coalition partner, the liberal FDP, gained nearly 5% points to give it 14.6% of the vote, the best result of its history.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The big loser of the election was the SPD, which received its worst result ever in a federal election, receiving only 23% of the total party vote and suffering the biggest percentage loss of any party in German federal election history in 60 years.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] The two other parties represented in the Bundestag, the Left and the Greens, both made large gains and received the highest vote share of their respective histories.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] For the first time, The Left won constituency seats outside its traditional stronghold of East Berlin.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] As a result of the losses by the SPD and the gains by the FDP, the alliance of the CDU/CSU and FDP received an outright majority of seats, ensuring that Angela Merkel would continue as chancellor.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] Had the CDU/CSU and FDP failed to win a majority of seats, possible alternative coalitions may have included a continuation of the grand coalition of CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:annette-faße/2009-german-federal-election] A traffic light coalition (SPD–FDP–Greens) was specifically ruled out by FDP leader Guido Westerwelle.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Despite similar names and somewhat similar goals, the institutions in Germany and Sweden are quite different from those in Denmark and Norway.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Folk high schools in Germany and Sweden are in fact much closer to the institutions known as *folkeuniversitet* in Norway and Denmark, which provide adult education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] However, unlike the *folkeuniversitet,* folk high schools in Sweden are not connected with a regular university.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The Finnish adult education centers called *työväenopisto*, *kansanopisto* and *kansalaisopisto* (Swedish: *arbetarinstitut*, literally 'workers' institute') are also part of the adult education tradition.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Note that the Finnish *kansanopisto* and *kansalaisopisto* are completely distinct institutions and function very differently despite having similar names.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Other countries have also been inspired by Grundtvig's concept of popular education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In Nigeria, the United States, and India, a few schools have been built upon Grundtvig's principles for education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Grundtvig, regarded as the founder of the folk high school, received inspiration for the concept from the English boarding schools, but Grundtvig's focus was not on formal education but on popular education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The idea was to give the peasantry and other people from the lower echelons of society a higher educational level through personal development; what Grundtvig called "the living word".
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The language and history of the fatherland, its constitution and main industries (farming) along with folk songs should be the guiding principles for an education based on a Christian framework.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The first folk high school was established in 1844 in Rødding, Denmark.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The school in Rødding, however, was somewhat aristocratic as chiefly civil servants and rich farmers were enrolled.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Another pioneer for the folk high school was the teacher Christen Kold.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] His, for that time, highly unorthodox way of teaching gave the folk high schools a broader democratic basis in comparison to the initial religious focus.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The teaching took place from November to March because students did farm work the rest of the year.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Kold's goal was for students to return to the school regularly in the winter to continue their education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In the beginning only young men could attend the courses, but in 1861 young women also gained access to folk high schools when teaching began being offered from May to July.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The men still only attended during winter.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The breakthrough for the idea was the Second War of Schleswig in 1864 when Denmark had to surrender a large part of its territory.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] This incident allowed the growth of a new Danish consciousness and nationalism based on enlightenment of the people.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Denmark's loss of territory to Prussia hit the Danish national consciousness hard, which became a catalyst for a new Danish identity.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] They established folk high schools all around the country and by 1867 twenty-one folk high schools had opened.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Almost everyone working at the folk high schools had been an apprentice of Grundtvig.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In 1918 the number of folk high schools in Denmark had reached 68.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Modern folk high schools vary significantly.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Some still have a religious focus but most of them are secular.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The schools are still *Grundtvigian* folk high schools which means that their focus is on enlightenment, ethics, morality and democracy although they are not taught explicitly.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The *Grundtvigian* philosophy is embedded in the teaching of various subjects, e.g. the arts, gymnastics and journalism.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Most of the schools have an area of expertise, such as sports, music or writing.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Since no degree or diploma is awarded at the end, the teaching is freer and more informal than at ordinary educational institutions.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Most Scandinavian folk high schools are boarding schools where the students live for from two to six months, though some schools offer programs for an entire year.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The movement started as a row with the old school.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Grundtvig fought for a public education as an alternative to the university elite.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The folk high schools should be for those wanting to *learn* in general and to help people form part of human relations and society.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The folk high schools have changed naturally – some also radically – through time, but many of Grundtvig's core ideas about the folk high school are still to be found in the way they are run today.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The folk high school of today is engaged in a complex modern reality and influenced both by national, international and global questions.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] One of the main concepts still to be found at the folk high schools today is "lifelong learning".
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] They should shed light on basic questions surrounding life of people both as individuals and as members of society.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] To Grundtvig the ideal was to give the students a sense of a common best and focusing on life as it really is.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Therefore, Grundtvig never set down guidelines for the future schools or a detailed description of how they should be run.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] He declared that the folk high schools should be arranged and developed according to life as it is and the schools should not hold exams because the education and enlightenment was a sufficient reward.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The essential element was and is the life at the schools.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] A folk high school becomes what it is because of the individuals of which it is made.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Learning happens across social positions and differences – the teacher learns from the student and vice versa in a living exchange and mutual teaching.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] For Grundtvig dialogue across differences was essential – the ideal was that people must learn to bear with the differences of each other before enlightenment can be realized.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Especially in non-German speaking countries, the folk high schools may be boarding schools or may mainly offer courses for adults age 18–30.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In addition to the Nordic countries and Germany there are also folk high schools in Switzerland, Austria, Poland, and France.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The Association for Community Colleges (ACC) advocated for European transnational Folk High Schools.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The first folk high school was founded in Rødding, Denmark, in 1844.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] It began on the initiative of Christen Kold, who was a follower of Grundtvig.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The school was inspired by the need to educate those not fortunate enough to have an education and the poor, or peasantry, who could not spare the time or the money to attend a university.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Among the other old folk high schools in Denmark are Testrup Folk High School (founded 1866), Askov Højskole (founded 1865) and Ry Højskole (founded 1892) in Jutland; Vallekilde Folk High School in Zealand (founded 1865), and Rødkilde Højskole on Møn (founded 1866).
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The International People's College in Helsingør is unique among the Danish folk high schools in that it is the most international one in Denmark, with classes taught in English and teachers and students from countries all around the world attending.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] There are around 70 folk high schools in Denmark.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The principal subjects of instruction vary from the creative arts such as music, arts, design, writing, to intellectual courses such as religion, philosophy, literature and psychology.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Some schools even have courses that specialize in sports.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Tuition varies, but is typically around 1300 Danish kroner per week, including board and lodging.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In recent history, globalization has exercised an increasingly important influence on Danish schools.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Many courses are open to foreigners as well as Danes, and many courses include travelling or voluntary stays in other countries as part of the curriculum.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In 1889, Sofia Hagman started the first folk high school in Finland in Kangasala.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Public, private, secular and religious folk high schools are common in Finland, and there are also worker's high schools, which are governed by the labor movement.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] There are 184 folk high schools in Finland, with an annual course attendance of 650,000, in 2 million hours of lessons, which are substantial numbers for a country of 5.5 million people.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Unlike in Finnish public education, there are tuition fees, per-course and per-lesson fees.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The most common subjects are handicraft skills, music, languages, physical education, visual arts, theater and dance.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Christian folk high schools offer religious instruction for laymen.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The schools offer also courses from the primary and secondary school curriculum, which allows for improving the grades from these levels later in life, even if the student has already graduated.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In 1866, during the Second Empire, Jean Macé founded the *Ligue de l'enseignement* ("Teaching League"), which was devoted to popular instruction.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The Jules Ferry laws that were passed in the 1880s established free, secular, mandatory public education as one of the founding principles of the Third Republic.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In addition, many teachers were strong supporters of Alfred Dreyfus during the Dreyfus Affair of the 1890s.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Afterward, some teachers set up free educational lectures on humanist topics in order to struggle against the spread of antisemitism in France.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In more recent times, following the 1981 presidential election Minister of Education Alain Savary supported Jean Lévi's initiative to create a public high school that would deliver the baccalauréat but would be organized on the principles of *workers' self-management* (or "autogestion").
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] This high school took the name *Lycée autogéré de Paris* (LAP).
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The LAP was explicitly inspired by the secondary school Vitruve, which opened in 1962 in the 20th arrondissement of Paris (and is still active), Oslo Experimental High School, which opened in 1967 in Norway, and Saint-Nazaire Experimental High School, which opened six months before the LAP.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Theoretical influences include the works of Célestin Freinet, Raymond Fonvieille, Fernand Oury, and other theoreticians of the institutional pedagogy, institutional analysis (René Lourau in particular), and institutional psychotherapeutic movements.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] This type of folk high school is currently most widespread in Germany.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Because they offer preparatory classes for school exams, in Germany these schools also function as the equivalent of adult high schools in other countries.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Germany also has folk high schools that are boarding schools, called *Heimvolkshochschulen*.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In Switzerland, the centers founded by Fritz Wartenweiler—such as "Nussbaum" in Frauenfeld (1919) and Herzberg in Densbüren (1935)—were unable to establish themselves partly due to the lack of educational leave for workers.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Conversely, evening folks high school achieved a certain degree of success.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The first of these were founded by bourgeois circles in 1919 in Basel, Zurich, Bern, and Lucerne, following the Swiss General Strike.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In French-speaking Switzerland, Ticino, and the Romansh-speaking parts of Grisons, these institutions did not appear until after the Second World War.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Geneva was an exception, as a "workers' university" (*université ouvrière*), linked to the labor movement, had existed there since 1900.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The popular universities, particularly those in Basel and Zurich, emerged as a reaction to the labor movement, which was perceived as a threat to the state.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] They viewed themselves as civic instruments for integrating the working class into the national community, of which they held an idealized view.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Their declared goal was to strengthen democratic capacity by enabling citizens to make informed decisions and by providing the lower social classes with access to university-level knowledge.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Although politically and denominationally neutral and intended to be open to all population groups, this objective was only partially realized.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In Basel during the 1923–1924 academic year, only 16% of those enrolled belonged to the working class.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] This was likely due in part to the academic format in which the courses were delivered.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In 1919–1920, 5,336 people attended twenty-one courses in Basel.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] It was not uncommon to see over 500 auditors at lectures given by university professors on subjects such as natural sciences, medicine, fine arts, music, literature, psychology, or philosophy.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] A comparison between the curricula of 1920 and the 1990s reveals a marked increase in language courses and a decline in interest in the natural sciences.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] While language courses—primarily utilitarian in nature—made up a good half of the offerings in 1995–1996, there was still debate in the 1950s as to whether this type of learning truly belonged in a popular university.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Themes related to personal development, continuing professional education, and leisure activities did not find a place in the programs until the 1960s.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The number of popular universities increased during the interwar period.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The Association of Swiss Popular Universities (VSV) was founded in 1943 to disseminate the movement's ideals more widely, facilitate the exchange of experiences, support emerging or expanding universities, and represent their interests to federal authorities.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The VSV is a member of the Swiss Federation for Adult Learning.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Folks high schools, whether cantonal or regional, are generally private law associations or foundations, often subsidized by cantons and municipalities.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] They exist in almost all cantons (known as *Corsi per adulti* in Ticino).
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Their administration is largely carried out by volunteers.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In the 2009–2010 academic year, they organized 10,563 courses attended by 154,753 people.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Despite efforts in the 1980s and 1990s to renew their offerings in terms of both content and methods, the popular university still struggles to shed its image as an institution dedicated to an elite culture, catering primarily to the middle-class demographic aged 40–60.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Iceland is home to only two folk schools, the LungA School, an artist-run art school in Seyðisfjörður, which opened in 2014 and the Flateyri Folk School in Flateyri, which opened in 2018.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Folk high schools (Lithuanian: *liaudies universitetas* which translates as people's university) were first established in the early 20th century in Lithuania.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] They became more popular in the interwar Lithuania.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In 1937, there were 56 people's universities attended by 160,000 students.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] After the Soviet occupation of Lithuania in 1940, the number of people's universities was reduced to eight attended by about 6,000 students.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The schools were completely closed after the German occupation in 1941.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The people's universities were reestablished in 1958 by the Ministry of Culture of the Lithuanian SSR.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] They were supervised by a council under the Lithuanian chapter of the Znanie Society.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In 1964, there were 18 people's universities in Vilnius that prepared training materials for other people's universities based in cities and districts.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The curriculum reflected Soviet ideology.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] After Lithuania regained independence in 1990, people's universities were closed.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Instead, cultural organizations (such as museums or libraries) organize educational activities (lectures, seminars, conferences, etc.).
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The first folk high school in Norway, Sagatun, was founded in 1864.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] As of 2012, there were 77 folk high schools spread across the country, thirty of which were Christian schools.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Folk high schools provide opportunities in general education, primarily for young adults.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] These schools are different from lower secondary schools, upper secondary schools, and higher education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] All students are eligible for normal financial aid.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Some folk high schools are connected to some sort of organization, but a large number of them are owned by a foundation and some are owned by the county.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Most courses last for one year, but a few schools give a second year course.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Common course options include outdoor skills, land use skills, the arts such as photography or painting, music such as jazz or rock, Norwegian language and culture, and travel skills.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In 1910, the *Przegląd Oświatowy* magazine published by the People's Libraries Society featured an article by Idzi Świtała, in which he reported on the success of Danish folk high schools in fostering the prosperity of the Danish countryside.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] This inspired Polish activist Antoni Ludwiczak to establish a similar school in partitioned Poland, also for Polish patriotic education in view of the Germanisation policy of the German authorities.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The establishment of the school was delayed by World War I.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The first Polish folk high school was eventually established in 1921 in Dalki after the restoration of independent Poland.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The second folk high school was founded in 1924 in Szyce near Kraków, and many more were founded in the interbellum and after World War II.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] As of May 1948, there were 63 folk high schools in Poland.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The first folk high schools in Sweden were established in 1868.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] The first school was open only to men, but already in 1870, the first folk high school for females was founded by Fredrique Paijkull.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Swedish folk high schools receive public funding from the Swedish government to support four goals: strengthening democracy, personal development, creating educational equality, and promoting interest and participation in culture.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] As of 2023, there are 156 folk high schools throughout the country, most of which are situated in the countryside, often in remote areas.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Tuition is free, and the students are eligible for normal financial aid for expenses such as accommodation and other school costs.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Students can either study for a general qualification, which makes them eligible to study at university, or a specific subject such as arts, crafts, film, theatre, music or design to gain practical experience.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Some schools, for example Södra Vätterbygdens Folkhögskola near Jönköping, cooperate with schools in other countries and have an exchange student program.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] A comprehensive overview of the programs offered at all Swedish folk high schools between 1952-2019 is provided in an open data repository and the central page for applying to folk high schools is folkhogskola.nu.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] In 1998, the Grundtvig Movement of Nigeria led by Dr.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Kachi Ozumba Snr. established Grundtvig International Secondary School, an independent co-educational secondary school built upon Grundtvig's principles for education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Campbell and Olive Dame Campbell helped create a folk high school in rural Appalachia based on observations of European folk high schools.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Campbell Folk School opened in 1925 in Brasstown, North Carolina, and it is still offering classes today.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Students can learn American traditional arts and crafts, including blacksmithing, ceramics, cooking, jewelry, dance and music.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Myles Horton, who co-founded the civil rights-focused Highlander Folk School in New Market, Tennessee in 1932, was also inspired by the Danish folk high school movement, as can be read in his autobiography *The Long Haul*.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] A contemporary wave of folk school founding in the United States began in the late 1990s and earlier 2000s.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] At the beginning of the 1990s, there were only twelve active folk schools.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Historically in the United States, only one to two such organizations were founded each decade; however, during the 1990s, this pattern began to change.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] Nine folk schools were founded in the late 1990s and by 2010 an additional twenty-two.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] As of 2019, the Folk Education Association of America reported over ninety-four active folk schools in twenty-five states.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education-center] These new folk schools, largely modeled after the John C Campbell Folk School, work to strengthen their communities through the practice and sharing of place-based cultural traditions and craft.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The World Bank's 2019 World Development Report on *The Changing Nature of Work* argues that adult learning is an important channel to help readjust workers' skills to fit in the future of work and suggests ways to improve its effectiveness.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The practice of adult education is referred to as andragogy to distinguish it from the traditional school-based education for children (pedagogy).
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The purposes and methods of adult education are diverse.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In a college or university the aim is typically related to personal growth or learning skills to improve employment options.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adult education that focuses specifically on the workplace is often referred to as human resource development.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Another possible motivation is to challenge or sustain certain values for their democratic society.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Outside of required training for specific employee positions adult education is voluntary.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In countries with advanced systems of adult education, professional development is available through post-secondary institutions and provide professional development through their ministry of education or school boards and through nongovernmental organizations.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In addition, there are programs about adult education for existing and aspiring practitioners offered, at various academic levels, by universities, colleges, and professional organizations.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adult educators have long maintained commitments to racial justice and other forms of social justice struggle which included extensive work at Freedom Schools during the Civil Rights Movement.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Contemporary commitments to racial justice in adult education include initiatives in the workplace and beyond.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Educating adults differs from educating children in several ways given that adults have accumulated knowledge and work experience which can add to the learning experience.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In a study, Greenberg compared the orthographic and phonological skills of functionally illiterate adults and children.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The study found that although functionally illiterate adults performed similarly in reading tasks, children were more successful in vocabulary and spelling tests.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] This means that functional illiterate adults are at a similar level of education as children, yet they differ in strengths of different skills.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adult education can be for vocational, social, recreational, or self-development.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] It can also be a form of social justice to provide accessible education to the disadvantaged.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adult education is based on a government's social policies.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Continuing education can help adults maintain certifications, fulfill job requirements, and stay up-to-date on new developments in their field.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] As the socio-economics of society progress so does the requirements of human quality.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In the 1960s, the proposition of "lifelong education" was put forward, which led to the change of contemporary educational concepts.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Therefore, its ultimate goal might be to achieve human fulfillment.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The goal might also be to achieve an institution's needs.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] For example, this might include improving its operational effectiveness and productivity.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] A larger scale goal of adult education may be the growth of society by enabling its citizens to keep up with societal change and maintain good social order.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] One fast-growing sector of adult education is English for speakers of other languages (ESOL), also referred to as English as a second language (ESL) or English language learners (ELL).
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] These courses are key in assisting immigrants with not only the acquisition of the English language, but the acclimation process to the culture of the United States as well as other English speaking countries like Canada, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Lindeman was the first expert who gave a systematic account of adult education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In his theory of education, education is regarded as a lifelong process.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] He pointed out that due to the constant development and change of social life and the surrounding environment, knowledge, and information are in a cycle of constant transmission, supplement and update, which requires people to keep learning to adapt to the changes in the outside world.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] At the same time, he believes that adult learners should not only learn for the needs of work and survival, but also have the opportunity to enrich themselves.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] He insists that adult education is an inspiring life-changing tool.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adult education should not only help people improve their skills and abilities in work, but also guide people to find happiness outside work.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Otherwise, Lindeman also proposed that the most valuable resource for adult learners is the learner's experience.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] He believes that the purpose of adult education is to give meaning to all kinds of experience.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Experience can enhance learners' autonomous learning and cognitive ability.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In addition, Lindeman believes that adult education is an important means of improving society.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The basic function of adult education is to promote the physical and mental development of adult learners.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] He argues that adult education is a powerful tool for social activists.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Through adult education, the personal code of conduct and cultural knowledge of adult learners should be improved to gradually improve the social atmosphere and order.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In the 1970s Malcolm Knowles introduced andragogy as the central theory of adult learning, defining andragogy as “the art and science of helping adults learn.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Andragogy is based on using the neurological and cultural differences in how adults learn to improve the quality of their education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Knowles's andragogy theory helps adults create new and strengthen current knowledge from previous experiences.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Andragogy involves planning coursework directly related to how it will the student will apply the content in their life.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] This brings an ever-expanding experience to use as an educational resource.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Teachers who use andragogy theory to design coursework find their students progress faster and are more successful in reaching their goals.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adults need to know why they need to learn something.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Knowles suggests these characteristics should be taken into consideration when designing programs for adults and facilitating adult learning processes.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] He also proposed a model of self-directed learning.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In Knowles's view, self-directed learning is a process in which individuals actively diagnose their learning needs, propose learning goals, select and implement appropriate learning strategies, and evaluate learning results.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Previous research findings suggest that as adults get older, they are less likely to participate in AE (adult education).
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The International Adult Literacy Survey (IALS), nationally representative samples of adults aged 16–65 in 23 OECD countries, has found that older age groups had lower participation rates than younger age groups.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Particularly, adults aged 16 to 25 were on average about three times more likely to participate than older adults aged 56 to 65.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Eurobarometer survey, national representative samples of adult aged 15 to 65 of European Union countries, also revealed that adults in the three youngest age groups examined (ages 15–24, ages 25–39, and ages 40–54) were more likely to participate in AE than age group of 55+.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Moreover, the Eurobarometer survey shows that participation rate declined from younger to older adults.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Participation rate of European countries was 59% for adults aged 15–24.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The rate began to decline 38% for adults aged 25–39 and it also fell down to 31% for adults aged 40–54.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Participation rate was 17% for adults above 55.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Reason of why older adults' participation declined relates mainly to lack of promotion and support.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] When people get old, their chances to take promotion for any AE programs are reduced.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In many OECD and European countries, employers often support their workers to attend in AE programs since they consider that workers with higher-educated and skilled are crucial indicators of development for companies.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Therefore, older adults cannot get promotions from their employers because of the gradual loss of seniority, learning ability and performance.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Since older adults are rarely offered a promotion from their employers, and the cost would be an obstacle for participation, they are unable to take the courses even if they wanted to take part in programs.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Moreover, lack of motivation and unavailability of learning opportunities could be additional reasons of older adults' low-participation).
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Findings of previous research are quite mixed when participation in AE comes to gender.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] According to the IALS, there is no a statistically significant difference between men and women in AE.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] However, the average participation rate of men was a bit higher than women.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] It was 38.7% for men and 37.9% for women.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The Eurobarometer survey shows a similar result to the IALS data.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Specifically the average participation of males was 35%; while, it was 30% for females.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Women's low participation is mainly resulted from family burdens and lack of financial support.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] However, an opposite tendency can be observed in the US.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] A study based on National Household Education Survey [NCES] in 2001 revealed that although gender difference did not exist much, females were more likely to participate in AE than males in the US.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The participation rate was 49% for women and 43% for men.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Educational attainment is determined as the most important factor in predicting participation in AE.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] It is known that those with higher levels of educational attainment participate more in AE programs.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The IALS showed that there was a clear relationship between previous educational attainment and participation in AE.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The data found those with low educational background were less likely to participate in OECD countries.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Specifically, the participation rate was 57.6% for adults who completed college or university education; while, it was 15.5% for adults who did not complete high school.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The Eurobarometer survey also showed that 87% of low-educated people belonged to the non-participant group.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Reason of low or non-participation of the less-educated can be explained from perspectives of individual and employers.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Individual point illustrated that low self-confidence regarding the learning, which mainly derived from previous bad educational experiences, could be a major obstacle for the less-educated.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Apart from low self-confidence, those less-educated might not perceive their need of participation or might actually not have a need to participate.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Yet, employers' view was apparent that they tended to support high-educated because they were more trainable than the low-educated.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Therefore, the participation of the less-educated was low since they could not get promotions from their employers.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Finally, adults who come from a better socio-economic background tend to participate more in AE programs.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The OECD data showed that higher the parent' educational level could produce the higher participation rate.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Summarizing above findings, people, those are young and men, with high levels of education, high-status of jobs are more likely to take part in any form of education and training.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] On the contrary, typical non-participants tend to be women, older, less educated, and coming from poor socio-economic backgrounds.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In addition, less-skilled, unemployed, immigrants, language minorities, and rural residents are less likely to participate in AE programs.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Deterrents are characteristics that explain why adults respond in negative manners to participate in education and learning.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Deterrents faced by adults are multifaceted, including both external and internal factors.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] However, cost and time have been remained as the most frequently reported deterrents.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Large sampled (nationwide and international) surveys on barriers to participation such as a study of National Center for Education Statistics (NCES) of the US, IALS and Eurobarometer indicated that time and cost were the main deterrents for adults.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Moreover, some empirical studies discovered time and cost as the most cited deterrents through studying various groups of adults.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Cost includes tuition fee of a program as well as extra expenditures for learning such as clothes, food, transportation and other school necessities (textbooks and stationaries).
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] It is well known that adults less educated, low-skilled and unemployed are less likely to participate in education/learning.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] For the unemployed, it is obvious that cost can hinder their participation in education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] And those lacking education and skills must be paid low salaries.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In this way, cost could be the most influential deterrent.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Even employed adults seem not wanting to invest money for a course, but they could attend if their employers supported them financially.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] For the time barrier, most adults involved in the above-mentioned studies reported that they could not participate in educational activities due to lack of time.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adults tended to say that they were busy with their daily routines.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Apart from cost and time deterrents, family and job commitments are other most commonly cited deterrents.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The large sampled surveys and empirical studies as mentioned earlier revealed that adults tended to report family and job responsibilities as deterrents and rated right after the cost and time deterrents.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] However, Milana suggested that busy workload and family responsibilities can be associated with the time barrier, otherwise time barrier itself is a vague concept.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adults feel they do not have time to learn because they are busy at work and home.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Thus, the time barrier should be considered in line with family and job commitments.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] After above-mentioned deterrents, another mostly reported deterrent is irrelevant and inadequate supplies of trainings/activities.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In other words, AE programs and courses do not always suit the needs of adult learners.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] It, therefore, is also important for educational planners to recognize that AE opportunities available may not always suit the learner's need.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Deterrents related to an individual's internal issues tend to be reported in lowest rate.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] For example, the IALS showed that the least deterrent was lack of self-confidence.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Also, the Eurobarometer survey indicated that adults’ perception of being too old to learn was the least significant deterrent.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Moreover, perceived deterrents are differentiated into social groups.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Johnstone and Rivera found that older adults faced more dispositional barriers such as low self-confidence and too late for being learners.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Also, younger adults and women were more experienced with situational barriers such as cost and child care arrangements.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Among the less educated, one's low-confidence regarding the learning ability could be the main deterrent.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Meanwhile, research illustrates that understanding the motivations and barriers of adult learners can increase their enrollment and retention.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Additional research shows that adult learners are more motivated in the classroom when they can clearly identify the application of their education to their professional or personal experiences.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] When instructors recognize their students' characteristics, they can develop lessons that address both the strengths and the needs of each student.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adults that are motivated, have confidence, and positive self-esteem are more likely to develop into lifelong learners.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In fast-developing countries, the qualifications of adults fall far behind those of young people, and may no longer match the requirements of a developed economy.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] This implies strong potential demand for the education and training of adults.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] This demand needs to be met through flexible modes of study which are suitable for adults, avenues of access that recognize informal prior learning, and the supports necessary for adults with limited formal education to succeed in further study.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Functional illiteracy is the inability to use reading, writing, and calculation skills to contribute to the development of personal and societal growth.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The person may have some knowledge, but not enough to understand and interact with the world which expects basic literacy.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adult education can have many benefits ranging from better health and personal well-being to greater social inclusion.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] It can also support the function of democratic systems and provide greater opportunities for finding new or better employment.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adult education has been shown to have a positive impact on the economy.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adult education provides opportunities for personal growth, goal fulfillment & socialization.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Chris McAllister's research of semi-structured interviews with older adult learners shows a motivation to communicate with people and to get out of the house to keep mentally active.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Researchers have documented the social aspects of older adult education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Friendship was described as an important aspect of adult learning.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The classroom is seen as a part of their social network.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In recent studies, the friendships that are made between adults seem to have an increasing effect on their social structure as a whole.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The development of social networks and support was found to be a key motivation of adult learners.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] As editor of a book entitled Adult Education and Health, Leona English claims that including health education as part of adult education makes for a healthier community.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] When surveying adult education programs in Japan, Nojima found that classes focusing on hobbies and very specific recreational activities were by far the most popular.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The author noted that more time, money and resources needed to be in place so participants would be able to take advantage of these types of activities.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Withnall explored the influences on later life learning in various parts in the U.K.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Results were similar in that later in life education afforded these older adults opportunities to socialize.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Some experts claim that adult education has a long-term impact on the economy and that there is a correlation between innovation and learning at the workplace.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Recently, adult education has gained recognition and importance in broader educational policies which emphasise inclusive and equitable education for all.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] However, there has been a shift towards a narrow focus on vocational skills, undermining the transformative potential of adult education.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Looking to the future, adult learning needs to extend beyond labor market needs, connecting career change and reskilling to broader educational reforms.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Lifelong learning should be reconceptualized as transformative and responsive to societal changes.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] It is crucial to address the participation and inclusion of vulnerable groups, appreciate informal learning, embrace digital means of participation, and promote scientific literacy while combating misinformation.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adult education plays a vital role in enhancing competencies, fostering responsibility, understanding changing paradigms, and shaping a just and sustainable world, emphasizing intergenerational solidarity.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Global Reports on Adult Learning and Education (GRALE) are a series of reports that monitor progress on Adult Learning and Education (ALE), promote action, identify trends in the field of ALE, and explore solutions to challenges.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] GRALE play a key role in meeting UNESCO's commitment to monitor and report on countries' implementation of the Belém Framework for Action.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] This Framework was adopted by 144 UNESCO Member States at the Sixth International Conference on Adult Learning and Education (CONFINTEA VI), which was held in Belém, Brazil, in 2009.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In the Belém Framework for Action, countries agreed to improve ALE across five areas of action: policy; governance; financing; participation, inclusion and equity; and quality.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] As of 2019, the global youth literacy rate is 91%, meaning 102 million youth lack basic literacy skills.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In low-income countries, one in three young people still cannot read.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The adult literacy rate as of 2019 is 86%, which means 750 million adults lack basic literacy skills.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] There are 92 literate women for every 100 literate men globally, and in low-income countries, as few as 77 literate women for every 100 literate men.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] The literacy rate is expected to continue to grow steadily in countries in all income groups.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] At the global level, the youth literacy rate is expected to reach 94% by 2030 and the adult literacy rate 90%.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] In low-income countries, less than 70% of adults and slightly more than 80% of youth aged 15 to 24 years are projected to have basic literacy skills by 2030.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Adult education is the challenge of balancing learning with other life responsibilities.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] Many learners juggle education with full time jobs, family, and financial pressures.
[src:annette-faße/adult-education] These factors make it difficult to prioritize and engage consistently in studying.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] After graduating from secondary school with Mittlere Reife, Annette Faße attended a school for educators, which she left as a state-certified educator.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] She then worked as the head of a kindergarten and later as an employee at a school for physically disabled children.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] She also worked independently in adult education and was chairwoman of the supervisory board of the adult education center in the Cuxhaven district until November 2023.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] Annette Faße is married and has two sons.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] She has been a member of the SPD since 1972 and was chairwoman of the SPD sub-district of Cuxhaven for many years.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] Since September 4, 2010, Annette Faße has been deputy chairwoman of the state party council of the SPD Lower Saxony.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] Annette Faße was a member of the German Bundestag for the first time from 1987 to 1990.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] She was again a member of the German Bundestag from 1994 until 2009.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] Here she was deputy spokesperson for the transport, construction and housing working group of the SPD parliamentary group from 1998 to 2002 and also for the tourism working group from 1998 to 2005.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] From 2002 to 2005 she was also deputy chair of the Committee on Transport, Construction and Housing.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] From January 2005 until 2009 she was the spokesperson for the SPD parliamentary group's tourism working group.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] Annette Faße entered the Bundestag in 1987 via the Lower Saxony state list and from 1994 onwards as a directly elected member of the Cuxhaven constituency and, since 2002, of the Cuxhaven – Osterholz constituency.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] In the 2005 federal election, she received 49.8% of the first votes there.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] In June 2008, Annette Faße announced that she would not run for the Bundestag again.
[src:annette-faße/annette-faße] She resigned from the Bundestag after the 2009 federal election.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The **Bundestag** (German: [ˈbʊndəstaːk] ⓘ, 'Federal Diet') is the federal parliament of Germany.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] It is the only constitutional body in the country directly elected by the German people.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag was established by Title III of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany (*Grundgesetz*) in 1949 as one of the legislative bodies of Germany, the other being the Bundesrat.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The members of the Bundestag are representatives of the German people as a whole, are not bound by any orders or instructions and are only accountable to their conscience.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Since the current 21st legislative period, the Bundestag has a fixed number of 630 members.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected every four years by German citizens aged 18 and older.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Elections use a mixed-member proportional representation system which combines first-past-the-post voting for constituency-seats with proportional representation to ensure its composition mirrors the national popular vote.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The German Bundestag cannot dissolve itself; only the president of Germany can do so under certain conditions.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of government at the federal level.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag is considerably more powerful than the Bundesrat, which represents the state governments.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] All bills must first be passed in the Bundestag before they are discussed in the Bundesrat.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundesrat can only accept laws passed by the Bundestag without amendment.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Only in some areas, where laws directly affect the states, can the Bundesrat reject laws; otherwise, it can only lodge an objection to them, which the Bundestag can overrule.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Above all, however, the chancellor and the federal government are solely responsible to the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag also has sole budgetary authority.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Since 1999, the Bundestag has met in the Reichstag building in Berlin.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag also operates in multiple new government buildings in Berlin around the neo-renaissance house and has its own police force (the *Bundestagspolizei*), directly subordinated to the Bundestag Presidency.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag's presiding officer is the president of the Bundestag; they are deputized by the Vice Presidents of the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Since 2025, Julia Klöckner of the CDU/CSU is the president of the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In the protocol order of the federation, the President of the Bundestag ranks second after the President and before the Chancellor.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The first body to be called Bundestag was the legislative body of the German Confederation, which convened in Frankfurt am Main from 1816 to 1866.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] This Bundestag was a convention of state envoys.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] During the revolution of 1848/49, the National Assembly, which met in Frankfurt am Main, was the first elected German parliament and served as a constituent assembly for a German state, which ultimately did not come to pass.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The North German Confederation, founded in 1866/67, was the first German nation state with an established elected parliament, however this ended up being called the Reichstag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In 1870/71, the federation was expanded to include the southern German territories and was henceforth called the German Empire.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Reichstag building, where the current Bundestag meets since 1999 (see below), was built in 1888.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The German Empire was not yet a parliamentary democracy in the modern sense, but a constitutional monarchy with democratic elements.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Reichstag had to approve all bills, had the right to initiate legislation and, in particular, had budgetary sovereignty.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] However, the Chancellor and the imperial government were not responsible to parliament, but to the emperor alone.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] It was not until 1918, a few weeks before the end of the First World War, that the Reichstag was given the right, as part of a constitutional reform, to withdraw its confidence in the Chancellor and thus force him to resign.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] There was also no universal suffrage for the Reichstag; only men over the age of 25 were entitled to vote in Reichstag elections.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] After its defeat in the First World War, Germany became a republic and a parliamentary democracy with the Weimar Constitution of 1919.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The voting age was lowered to 21 years and women were given the right to vote for (and serve in) the Reichstag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] However, the first German democracy failed for various reasons, some of which were directly related to the Reichstag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The pure proportional representation system in elections did not produce clear majorities and the various parties were not sufficiently willing to compromise to form stable governments.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] This led to numerous changes of government and snap elections.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In the last years of the Weimar Republic, opposition parties on the far-right and the far-left held the majority of seats in the Reichstag, which led the governments to rule largely by emergency decrees and bypass parliament.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In 1933, Adolf Hitler was appointed chancellor and through the Reichstag Fire Decree, the Enabling Act of 1933 and the death of President Paul von Hindenburg in 1934, gained unlimited power.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] After this, the Reichstag, in which only the Nazi Party was represented from November 1933 on, met only rarely, above all to extend the emergency laws on which the Nazi dictatorship was formally based.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] With the Basic Law of 1949, Germany's second democratic constitution, the Bundestag was established as the new parliament.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Due to the division of Germany, the Bundestag was de facto a West German parliament until 1990.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The socialist GDR in East Germany had its own parliament, the Volkskammer, which, however, did not emerge from democratic elections except for its last electoral term in 1990.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Because West Berlin was not officially under the jurisdiction of the Basic Law during the division, the Bundestag met in Bonn in several different buildings, including (provisionally) a former waterworks facility and finally in the Bundeshaus.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In addition, owing to the city's legal status, citizens of West Berlin were unable to vote in elections to the Bundestag, and were instead represented by 22 non-voting delegates chosen by the House of Representatives, the city's legislature.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Since German reunification in 1990, the Bundestag has once again been an all-German parliament.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In 1999, the German parliament moved from Bonn to Berlin and sits once again in the Reichstag building.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of the German political system.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag is one of three constitutional bodies (along with the Bundesrat and the federal government) that have the right of initiative for the legislative process.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In order to introduce a bill in the Bundestag, the support of a faction or of a number of MPs corresponding to at least 5% of all MPs is required.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] All bills (including those introduced by the Bundesrat and the government) are first voted on in the Bundestag (for bills from the Bundesrat and the government, however, an opinion must first be obtained from the other body).
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] A bill is first discussed at first reading, then referred to one or more committees, where it can be amended; the resulting committee version then goes back to the plenary, where it is passed at second and third reading.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Amendments can also be tabled at this stage.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] A simple majority (more yes votes than no votes with no regard to abstentions) is required for normal legislative proposals.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In some very rare cases, the Basic Law requires the so-called chancellor majority (majority of all members of parliament) for simple laws, for example to establish new intermediate and subordinate federal authorities.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Laws amending the Basic Law require a two-thirds majority of all members of the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] A law passed by the Bundestag is passed on to the Bundesrat.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Amendments to the Basic Law and laws that directly affect the states must be passed by the Bundesrat by majority vote (amendments to the Basic Law, again, by a two-thirds majority); all other laws are considered passed if the Bundesrat does not object to them within 14 days.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In no case can the Bundesrat make amendments to a bill.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] If the Bundesrat rejects a bill, the matter is often referred to the so-called mediation committee, a body made up of an equal number of members of the Bundestag and Bundesrat, which attempts to negotiate whether the bill can find the approval of both chambers with certain amendments.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] A version amended in this way must then be passed again by a majority in both chambers in order to become law (in this case the rules of procedure of both chambers provide for an abbreviated legislative procedure).
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In the final step, a law must be signed by the President of Germany (they have a right of veto in theory, but this has been used very rarely in the history of the Federal Republic).
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag has an elective function for a number of offices.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The chancellor is elected by the Bundestag and formally appointed by the president of Germany.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] A chancellor's election is necessary whenever the office of chancellor has fallen vacant.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] This is the case if a newly elected Bundestag meets for the first time, or during legislative periods, if the former chancellor died or resigned.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The chancellor's election is one of the few cases in which a vote in the Bundestag requires a majority of all elected members, not just a majority of those assembled at the time, the so-called *Kanzlermehrheit* ("chancellor majority").
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] As with other elections performed by the Bundestag, the chancellor is elected via secret ballot.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] If the nominee reaches the necessary "chancellor majority", the president appoints him or her and, after that, the president of the Bundestag will administer the oath of office before the assembled house.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] If this nominee is not elected, the right of nomination is transferred onto the Bundestag: Candidates can now be nominated for election, whereby a nomination must be supported by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag can hold any number of ballots in this manner for two weeks.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] To be elected, a candidate still needs a "chancellor majority" of yes-votes ("Second voting phase").
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] If the Bundestag is unable to elect a chancellor in these fourteen days, a final ballot is held on the very next day.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Once again, candidates can be nominated by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Candidates receiving a "chancellor majority" in this ballot are elected.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Otherwise, it is up to the President of Germany either to appoint the candidate with the plurality of votes as Chancellor or to dissolve the Bundestag and call new elections ("Third voting phase").
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Another possibility to vote a new chancellor into office is the constructive vote of no confidence, which allows the Bundestag to replace a sitting chancellor, if it elects a new chancellor with the "chancellor-majority".
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag shares responsibility with the Bundesrat for electing the judges of the Federal Constitutional Court.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Both chambers elect four judges to each of the court's two senates.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] They also elect the president and vice-president of the Federal Constitutional Court in alternating order.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In the Bundestag, this requires a two-thirds majority of members present, which has equal at least a majority of all members.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The majority ratios in the Bundestag therefore do not necessarily have to correspond to those in the Federal Assembly.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected for four years, and new elections must be held no earlier than 46 and no later than 48 months after the beginning of a given legislative term.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] By way of exception, there may be an early election if the President of Germany dissolves the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] However, the President only has the right to do so in the event of a failed chancellor election or if an incumbent chancellor requests dissolution after losing a vote of confidence.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The possibility of an early election is therefore in theory much more limited than is the case in some other parliamentary democracies.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] This restriction is intended to encourage the parliamentary groups to cooperate in difficult situations, and is a lesson learned from the experience of the Weimar Republic, in which snap elections were very frequent because the parties were unable to compromise and form stable governments.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] A legislative term ends at the moment when a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for the first time, which must occur within 30 days after an election.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The principle applies that there can be no "period without parliament".
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] An elected Bundestag is fully competent to act until a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for its first session.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Prorogations and dissolutions (in the strict sense), as known in the Westminster system, do not exist in Germany.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Even an early dissolution of the Bundestag, as described above, in practice only leads to an early election, but does not end the legislative period itself.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Following the tradition of German parliamentarism, the Bundestag is subject to the *principle of discontinuation*, meaning that a newly-elected Bundestag is legally regarded as a body and entity completely different from the previous Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] This leads to the result that any motion, application or action submitted to the previous Bundestag, e.g. a bill referred to the Bundestag by the Federal Government, is regarded as void by non-decision (German terminology: "*Die Sache fällt der Diskontinuität anheim*").
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Thus any bill that has not been decided upon by the beginning of the new electoral period must be brought up by the government again if it aims to uphold the motion, this procedure in effect delaying the passage of the bill.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Furthermore, any newly-elected Bundestag will have to freshly decide on the rules of procedure (*Geschäftsordnung*), which is done by a formal decision of taking over such rules from the preceding Bundestag by reference.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] If the succeeding Bundestag convenes with same or similar majorities like its predecessor, the parliament can decide to take over earlier initiatives of legislation in the same fashion to abbreviate the process, thus effectively breaking the principle of discontinuation by a pull.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Before an electoral reform in 2023, the Bundestag nominally had 598 members, with the mixture of majority and proportional representation regularly leading to a large number of additional overhang and compensation mandates.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Every elector has two votes: a constituency vote (first vote) and a party list vote (second vote).
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Based solely on the first votes, 299 members are elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The second votes are used to produce proportionality with respect to the total number of 630 seats; first at the federal level and then at state level (using the Sainte-Laguë method).
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In most cases, the number of constituencies won by a party in a given state does not exactly correspond to the number of seats to which the party is entitled in that state via second votes.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] To qualify for any seats, however, a party must either win three single-member constituencies via first votes (basic mandate clause) or exceed a threshold of 5% of the second votes nationwide.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] This does not apply to independent constituency candidates: these always enter the Bundestag if they win their constituency.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] (However, no independent constituency candidate has won a constituency since 1949).
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Seats allocated in this way are subtracted from the base number of 630 when the mandates are distributed among the parties.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In addition, the second votes of voters who have elected a successful independent candidate in a constituency are not taken into account when calculating the number of mandates (although they are for the 5% threshold).
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Parties representing recognized national minorities (currently Danes, Frisians, Sorbs, and Romani people) are exempt from both the 5% national threshold and the basic mandate clause.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The only party that has been able to benefit from this provision so far at the federal level is the South Schleswig Voters' Association, which represents the minorities of Danes and Frisians in Schleswig-Holstein, and succeeded in winning a seat in 1949, 2021, and 2025.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] If a member of parliament leaves the Bundestag during the current legislative term, either through resignation or death, another candidate from that party from the corresponding state takes their place.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Successful constituency candidates who did not receive a seat in the previous election due to the principle of second vote coverage are considered first, followed by the candidates on the respective state list.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] However, if the list is exhausted, the seat in question remains vacant for the remainder of the term.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] If the departing member was an independent constituency candidate, the seat also remains empty.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The latest federal election was held on Sunday, 23 February 2025, to elect the members of the 21st Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The executive bodies of the Bundestag are the Presidium and the Council of Elders.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Presidium consists of the President, the presiding officer, and several Vice Presidents.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The President and Vice Presidents are elected by the plenary of the Bundestag, whereby traditionally the largest fraction nominates the President and each fraction may nominate a vice president.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In addition to the members of the Presidium, the Council of Elders includes 23 other deputies who are delegated proportionally by the factions.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The council is the coordination hub, determining the daily legislative agenda and assigning committee chairpersons based on Parliamentary group representation.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The council also serves as an important forum for interparty negotiations on specific legislation and procedural issues.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Presidium is responsible for the routine administration of the Bundestag, including its clerical and research activities.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag cannot be adjourned or prorogued during the current legislative term, but is always fully capable of acting and sets its own legislative calendar.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Normally, the Bundestag sits for at least twenty weeks per year, interrupted by non-sessional weeks, especially a long parliamentary summer recess, during which the MPs are present in their constituencies.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The course of a session week is traditionally always the same: meetings of the parliamentary faction's internal committees take place on Monday and Tuesday mornings, and meetings in the faction-plenary on Tuesday afternoon.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] From Wednesday to Friday, plenary sessions and committee meetings take place in parallel (this is the reason why often very few members are present at plenary debates).
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Committee meetings are interrupted on very important items on the agenda so that all MPs have the opportunity to be present in the plenary hall.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The highlights of the procedures include government statements by the Chancellor and the general debate at the beginning of the annual budget deliberations, during which there is a direct clash between the Chancellor and the opposition leader.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Independently of the usual procedure, the Bundestag can also convene for extraordinary sessions at any time.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] This must happen if one third of the MPs, the President of Germany or the Chancellor request it (Basic Law, Article 39.3).
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The most important organisational structures within the Bundestag are 'factions' (*Fraktionen*; sing.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] A parliamentary faction must consist of at least 5% of all members of parliament.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Members of parliament from different parties may only join in a faction if those parties did not run against each other in any German state during the election.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Normally, all parties that surpassed the 5%-threshold build a faction of their own.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The CDU and CSU however, have always formed a joint faction, called CDU/CSU or Union.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] This is possible, as the CSU only runs in the state of Bavaria and the CDU only runs in the other 15 states.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The size of a faction determines the extent of its representation on committees, the time slots allotted for speaking, the number of committee chairs it can hold, and its representation in executive bodies of the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The factions, not the members, receive the bulk of government funding for legislative and administrative activities.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The leadership of each *Fraktion* consists of a parliamentary party leader, several deputy leaders, and an executive committee.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The leadership's major responsibilities are to represent the *Fraktion*, enforce party discipline and orchestrate the party's parliamentary activities.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The members of each *Fraktion* are distributed among working groups focused on specific policy-related topics such as social policy, economics, and foreign policy.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The *Fraktion* meets every Tuesday afternoon in the weeks in which the Bundestag is in session to consider legislation before the Bundestag and formulate the party's position on it.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Parties that do not hold 5% of the Bundestag-seats may be granted the status of a *group* in the Bundestag; this is decided case by case, as the rules of procedure do not state a fixed number of seats for this.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] This status entails some privileges which are in general less than those of a faction.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Most of the legislative work in the Bundestag is the product of standing committees, which exist largely unchanged throughout one legislative period.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The number of committees approximates the number of federal ministries, and the titles of each are roughly similar (e.g., defense, agriculture, and labor).
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] There are, as of the current nineteenth Bundestag, 24 standing committees.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The distribution of committee chairs and the membership of each committee reflect the relative strength of the various Parliamentary groups in the chamber.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] In the current nineteenth Bundestag, the CDU/CSU chaired ten committees, the SPD five, the AfD and the FDP three each, The Left and the Greens two each.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Members of the opposition party can chair a significant number of standing committees (e.g. the Budget Committee of the Bundestag was by tradition chaired by the biggest opposition party, until the 21st Bundestag, when Alternative for Germany was denied this post).
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] These committees have either a small staff or no staff at all.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The members of Bundestag and the presidium are supported by the Bundestag Administration.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] It is headed by the Director, that reports to the President of the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag Administrations four departments are Parliament Service, Research, Information / Documentation and Central Affairs.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag Administration employs around 3,000 employees.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Also following the tradition of German diets, the German Bundestag can legally convene on any location, domestic and foreign.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Reichstag plenary chamber is not determined by law as the location of the assembly, making it a facility of convenience.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Bundestag's predecessor, the German Reichstag, convened in the Kroll Opera House in Berlin, after the Reichstag with its then wooden interior and walls burned down in the Reichstag fire.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] After World War II, the Bundestag did not have own facilities to call home and had to convene in the Bundeshaus in Bonn together with the Bundesrat.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] 1953, the plenary chambers in the Bundeshaus had to be expanded and the Bundestag assembled in a radio building in Cologne.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Until 1965, the Bundestag assembled in West Berlin for nine sessions.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Seven sessions have been held in the Technische Universität Berlin and two sessions in Berlin's Congress Hall in Tiergarten.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The assemblies met severe protest from the communist side, the last session even interrupted by Soviet aircraft in supersonic low-altitude flight.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] 1971, the four occupying powers agreed to not accept Bundestag assemblies in West Berlin anymore.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled in the Old Waterworks Building in Bonn when the old plenary chamber had to get broken down, and in the new plenary chamber for only a few years after Germany's reunification.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The most distinctive assembly of the Bundestag outside its regular chambers was on 4 October 1990, the day after German reunification.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled inside the Reichstag building in Berlin for the first time after 57 years, and remote from its then-regular home in Bonn.
[src:annette-faße/bundestag] Soon after this most memorable assembly, the Bundestag decided to move from Bonn back to Berlin by a law which sets only the city of Berlin to be the home of the Bundestag, not the building.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven-district] The district was established in 1977 by merging the former districts of Land Hadeln and Wesermünde.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven-district] The town of Cuxhaven lost its status as a district-free town and became the capital of the new district.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven-district] The district is often nicknamed Cuxland.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven-district] It is located on the coast of the North Sea and is enclosed by the river mouths of Elbe and Weser.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven-district] The coasts are part of the Lower Saxony Wadden Sea National Park.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven-district] The arms display Saint Nicholas, who is the patron saint of fishermen.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven-district] The coast of the North Sea is symbolised at the bottom of the arms.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] Cuxhaven is home to an important fisherman's wharf and ship registration point for Hamburg as well as the Kiel Canal until 2008.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The city and its precursor Ritzebüttel belonged to Hamburg from the 13th century until 1937.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] What remains of Ritzebüttel is Ritzebüttel Castle ('*Schloss Ritzebüttel*').
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The island of Neuwerk, a Hamburg dependency, is located just northwest of Cuxhaven in the North Sea.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The city's symbol, known as the Kugelbake, is a beacon once used as a lighthouse; the wooden landmark on the mouth of the Elbe marks the boundary between the river and the North Sea and also adorns the city's coat of arms.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] Ritzebüttel, today a part of Cuxhaven, belonged to the Land of Hadeln, first an exclave of the younger Duchy of Saxony and after its de facto dynastic partition in 1296 of the Duchy of Saxe-Lauenburg, established *de jure* in 1260.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] In 1394 the city of Hamburg conquered the fortress of Ritzebüttel and made it its stronghold to protect the estuary of the river Elbe, which connects that city with the open sea.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The population in 1848 was about 800 inhabitants.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The Hamburg America Line built a large ocean liner terminal at Cuxhaven in 1900.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] Connected directly to Hamburg by a dedicated railway line and station, it served as the major departure point for German and European emigrants until 1969 when ocean liner travel ceased.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The ornate assembly hall and associated buildings survived wartime damage and peacetime urban renewal to be restored in 1998 for use as a museum and cruise ship terminal.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] On 15 March 1907 Cuxhaven gained city status within the state of Hamburg.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] In 1937 Cuxhaven became an urban district of the Stade Region within the Prussian Province of Hanover by the Greater Hamburg Act.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] In 1972 some municipalities of the neighboured rural district of *Land of Hadeln* were incorporated into the urban district of Cuxhaven.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] In 1977 Cuxhaven lost the status as urban district and was integrated into the new rural District of Cuxhaven, being its capital.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] During the First World War Nordholz Airbase with its airship hangars, near Nordholz to the south of Cuxhaven, was one of the major Imperial German Navy airship stations.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] On Christmas Day 1914 it was attacked by Royal Navy seaplanes in the Cuxhaven Raid.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] It subsequently became a strategically important city as German authorities and civilians feared it would be the site of an Allied invasion.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] During the Second World War, the town hosted a base of a Wehrmacht radio network, codenamed BROWN, which transmitted data regarding experimental weapon developments, including rocketry.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] From this location the last ENIGMA-code–encrypted message of the war was transmitted on 7 May 1945.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] Between 1945 and 1964 the Hermann-Oberth-Gesellschaft performed various civilian experiments in rocketry near Cuxhaven.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The origins of tourism go back to the year 1816 when a seaside resort was founded in Cuxhaven.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] Since 1964 Cuxhaven has been a state-recognized climate seaside resort (*Seeheilbad*) and centre of the so-called holiday region of Cuxland.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] In the village of *Lüdingworth*, in the southern part of the town, stands the *Jacobikirche, Saint Jack's Church*.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] Due to its organ by Arp Schnitger and its lavish baroque interior, the building is one of the most notable of its kind in all Lower Saxony.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The island of Neuwerk is situated 8 kilometres (5 mi) off the coast from Cuxhaven.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] At low tide the water recedes so far from the coast that the island can be reached either by mudflat hiking or by horse carriage.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] A modern landmark of Cuxhaven is the Friedrich-Clemens-Gerke Tower, a telecommunication tower built of concrete, which is not accessible to the public.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] It is not really a landmark, for many cities in Germany have a similar tower.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The high-test peroxide (HTP) submarine *U1407* was raised from where she had been scuttled in Cuxhaven after WWII and rebuilt by the British, being commissioned as HMS *Meteorite*.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] It was the catalyst for a series of German-made air-independent propulsion submarines such as the Type 212 and Type 214.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The Cuxport deep-water port has begun operations in 1997.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] It is crucial for the continued economic development of the city of Cuxhaven and its surrounding area.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] Until 1993, the site of the new port belonged to the Free and Hanseatic City of Hamburg.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] After long negotiations with Hamburg this land became the property of the state of Lower Saxony, which then invested approximately €140 million in the construction of the new port facilities.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] There are six berths at two terminals (Europakai and Lübbertkai).
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The port is located at the Elbe estuary, near the Kiel Canal to the Baltic Sea.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The Cuxhaven multi-purpose terminal is (as of July 2025) operated by Cuxport GmbH, a subsidiary of Rhenus AG & Co.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] KG (74.9%) and the Hamburg-based HHLA (Hamburger Hafen und Logistik AG, 25.1%).
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The main businesses are RoRo transport, new vehicle storage and shipping (295,644 units in 2021), container handling, and the storage and handling of plant components for offshore wind farms.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] Components such as tower sections, rotor blades, and nacelles for onshore wind turbines are also handled.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] In 2021, about 2.448 million tonnes of goods were handled in maritime transport.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] The offshore infrastructure sector is significantly expanded in 2025-2029.
[src:annette-faße/cuxhaven] Cuxhaven has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*; Trewartha: *Dobk*), located on the North Sea coast, the weather is noticeably warmer in winter and cooler in summer.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The **German federal election system** regulates the election of the members of the national parliament, called the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] According to the principles governing the law of elections, set down in Art.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] 38 of the German constitution, elections are to be universal, direct, free, equal, and secret.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Furthermore, the constitution stipulates that Bundestag elections are to take place every four years and that one can vote, and be elected, upon reaching the age of 18.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] All other stipulations for the federal elections are regulated by the Federal Electoral Act.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Elections always take place on a Sunday.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Mail votes are possible upon application.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Germans elect their members of parliament with two votes.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The first vote is for a *direct candidate*, who is required to receive a plurality vote in their electoral district.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The second vote is used to elect a party list in each state as established by its respective party caucus.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The Bundestag comprises, then, the seats representing each electoral district on the first vote and the seats allocated to maintain proportionality based on the second vote.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Common practice is that direct candidates are also placed on the electoral lists at higher rankings as a fall-back in case they do not win their districts.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] An election is general if basically every citizen can take part: no restrictions in terms of income, sex, health, or any other arbitrary distinctions.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] But according to the jurisdiction of the Federal Constitutional Court, the prescription of a minimum voting age is compatible with the commonalty of the election.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The exclusion from the active right to vote is also—within narrow limitations—consistent with the Basic Constitutional Law.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The exclusion of the passive right to vote is governed by somewhat less strict regulations.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The right to vote is in principle reserved for German citizens and the so-called "status Germans," who are refugees and expelled persons of German descent that settled in Germany.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The introduction of a right to vote for foreigners would require an alteration of §20 of the constitution.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] An election is immediate if the voters' will determines the result directly.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The process of an election based on lists compiled by the political parties is, however, compatible with the principle of an immediate election.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] An election is considered free if the government does not compel the people's voting decision in terms of content.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] According to the Federal Constitutional Court's dispensation of justice, the principle of a free ballot would not be harmed if a compulsory vote was introduced by the Federal Electoral Law.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Electoral advertising at government expense would, however, be incompatible with this principle of electoral law.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] However, the Federal Government (made up of different political parties) is allowed to conduct public relations if its neutrality is strictly preserved.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Elections are confidential if the voter's decision is not known to anybody else.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The German Parliament's voting law even states that no elector is allowed to announce his decision in the polling station.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Postal voting is problematic because the secrecy of the ballot is not guaranteed; it has therefore to be taken as an exceptional case.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Since the election's more important basic principle of universal suffrage would otherwise be violated, postal votes are admissible.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In principle, an election is considered equal if all electoral votes have the same weight.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This is, for example, not the case if constituencies differ considerably in size or if gerrymandering causes advantages or disadvantages for certain groups of people.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] For electoral lawmaking, the most difficult part in terms of constitutional principles is the equality of the election.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] On the one hand, certain inequalities are unavoidable as the constituencies can not be of exactly equal size and the turnout, too, is not homogenous.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] On 3 July 2008, the Federal Constitutional Court declared the paradox of the *negatives Stimmgewicht* to be unconstitutional.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The court allowed three years for these changes, so the 2009 federal election was not affected.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The changes were due by 30 June 2011, but appropriate legislation was not completed by that deadline.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] A new electoral law was enacted in late 2011, but declared unconstitutional once again by the Federal Constitutional Court upon lawsuits from the opposition parties and a group of some 4,000 private citizens.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The five percent rule and the overhang are in principle approved by the Federal Constitutional Court and the German jurisprudence.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] All German citizens over the age of 18 are allowed to vote (Art.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] 2 of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany), as long as they have lived in Germany after reaching the age of 14 for at least a three-month continuous period that was within 25 years of the election.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] 1 all power emanates from the people, that is the people of Germany.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] 1 of German Federal Electoral Law determines in accordance with constitutional law, that only Germans in the sense of Art.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Every German who has reached the age of majority, in Germany 18 years, is eligible to stand for election according to the German Basic Law (article 38, paragraph 2 BL).
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] It has to be remarked that the age of majority can be altered by a simple federal law.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Eligibility to stand for election presupposes the right to vote.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] However, some German citizens are not permanent residents of Germany and also do not have the right to vote as a German citizen living abroad.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] They can still be elected if they meet all the other requirements.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Yet, people can be deprived of their eligibility to stand for election in certain circumstances.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This can happen in the case of an imprisonment of more than a year as is laid down in § 45, subparagraph 1 in the *Strafgesetzbuch*, the German criminal law.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The most important election management body is the Federal Returning Officer, appointed by the Federal Ministry of the Interior.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Responsibilities include running electoral procedures and chairing the election committee.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The leader of the Federal Statistical Office usually holds this office.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The Federal Returning Officer is assisted by the electoral committee and the Returning Officers of each *Bundesland*, the election supervisors and the electoral committee of each constituency as well as the election judges and the managing committee of each electoral ward.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] They are appointed by the federal government.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The other members of the electoral committees are appointed by the Returning Officer.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Election management bodies (EMBs) are institutions of independent, societal self-organisation.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In general they are considered to be a sort of federal agency.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The Federal Ministry of the Interior, the Supreme Federal Authority, is responsible for the enactment of certain regulations necessary for federal election procedures.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] However, the Federal Ministry of the Interior does not have the authority to issue directives against the election management bodies.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Within two months after the federal election (German: *Bundestagswahl*) any voter can request the scrutiny of elections.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The Committee for the Scrutiny of Elections only makes sure that the Federal Voting Act is implemented properly; it does not deal with possible unconstitutionalities.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] If the *Bundestag* rejects the veto, an appeal to scrutiny of elections can be lodged to the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany within another two months.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This appeal has to be joined by 100 eligible voters.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Affected members lose their seat in parliament if the veto is successful.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This member can in turn file a lawsuit against the adjudication.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] No appeal to scrutiny of elections against decisions made by the German *Bundestag* has thus far been successful.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Political parties are required to be membership-based, and the party determines its membership based upon its own bylaws, i.e., the party itself determines who can join, leave, and who is excluded from the party.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Applications for membership may be rejected without justification, and party bylaws may impose requirements and restrictions on membership, but may not discriminate based on gender, age, religion or ethnicity.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] All parties have membership fees, which range from 0.5%–4.0% of members' salaries, with reduced fees for low-income members.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] As parties can reject applications without justification, it is possible to discriminate unofficially.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Similarly to other parties using male pronouns for all genders, the feminist party Die Frauen even calls all its members women in its bylaws, but claims this term also applies to men.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Only parties that have been represented in the Bundestag or a Landtag by at least five delegates since the last election are entitled to propose their own candidates.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Other parties have to announce their candidature to the Federal Returning Officer in time, i.e. not later than 90 days before the election day of periodic elections of the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] They must have been accepted as a party by the Federal Electoral Committee beforehand.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The applicants from a party must be elected in a democratic and secret election by an assembly of the party members in a constituency or by a similar board appointed by the party.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Every party member entitled to vote is allowed to propose candidates.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] A candidate does not have to be a member of the party.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Since the 2009 German Bundestag elections no member of a different party may be nominated.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] A written record of the election must be presented to the District Returning Officer, who is responsible for checking the proposal.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] He points out possible deficiencies and allows remedies to be made.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] A constituency election nomination is only accepted if the nominee belongs to a party that is represented in the Bundestag or the Landtag, or if the party represents a national minority.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Otherwise the nominee must have at least 200 signatures from eligible voters in the constituency.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] It does not make a difference whether the suggestion is handed in by a party or not.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Hence a candidate does not need to be supported by a party in a constituency if he has sufficient signatures.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The county election nominee must also nominate a person of trust and a proxy who are allowed to release statements to the leader of the county election.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] A constituency election nomination can be recalled either by a joint statement from the two persons of trust or by a statement from the majority of the signataries of the nominee.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Through a declaration from the two persons of trust the name of the suggested person can be changed in case the originally suggested person loses his eligibility or dies.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Once the nomination is authorised it can neither be recalled nor changed.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] If a candidate with a direct mandate dies before election day, the election is cancelled in that constituency.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Within the next six weeks, a by-election is held, giving the opportunity to the deceased candidate's party to appoint a substitute candidate.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This by-election follows the same rules as the main election.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This means that Germans who have come of age in the time between the main and the by-election are not allowed to vote.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] According to the Federal Election Law the nominations for the regional lists basically result from the same system as the constituency nominations.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In addition, the order of the regional list is determined by secret election.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The regional list of a party which is neither represented in the Federal Parliament nor in a State Parliament and which does not represent a national minority, requires for its admission the signing of at least one-thousandth of the state's eligible voters, not exceeding 2,000 signatures.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] For the nomination of confidants and the modification of the regional list, the regulations concerning the constituency nominations are applied correspondingly.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] For the calculation of the electoral threshold, the candidate lists on state level of one party are generally treated as connected, unless the confidants issue a differing declaration to the Federal Returning Officer.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The federal election system distinguishes between 'first' and 'second' votes.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] However, these terms refer neither to a hierarchical order of importance of the votes, nor to a logical (chronological) sequence in a valid election process.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] According to public polls, between 63% (2005) and 70% (2002) of voters mistakenly thought the first vote to be more important than the second.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In some state election systems that have two voting systems modelled after the federal election setup, the votes are called 'vote for person' and 'vote for list'.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] It is important that both votes have distinct functions.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The first vote allows the elector to vote for a direct candidate of their constituency, who applies for a direct mandate in the Bundestag (see illustration above, no.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] A plurality voting system is used, which means that the candidate who receives more votes than any other candidate gets the mandate.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] If the vote results in a tie, the lot drawn by the leader of the regional election is decisive.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In this case, the votes for the other candidates are invalid.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The primary function of the first vote is to personalize the election.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] As there are 299 constituencies at the moment, the same number of mandates in the Bundestag are distributed to the elected candidates in each district.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] However, the first vote does not determine the power of the parties in the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] For each direct mandate in a Bundesland the party always receives one mandate fewer from the second vote.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The size and the geographical shape of the electoral constituencies are revised by an electoral committee appointed by Germany's Head of State.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The final decision is made by the German Bundestag and can be found in an attachment to the federal electoral law.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] For the distribution of seats in the German Bundestag, the second vote is more important than the first vote.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This second vote allows the elector to vote for a party whose candidates are put together on the regional electoral list.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Based on the proportion of second votes, the 598 mandates are distributed to the parties which have achieved at least 5 percent of valid second votes (i.e. reached the electoral threshold).
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Following the 1987 German Bundestag elections, the distribution of seats was made according to the Hare-Niemeyer method.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Due to a change in the law passed in January 2008, the distribution of seats is now made according to the Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The proportion of seats a party gets in the Bundestag approximately equates to the percentage of votes the party gets in the election.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Discrepancies result from overhang and the electoral threshold.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] 1, clause 2 of the Federal Election Law the electors' second votes are not accounted for if those electors give their first votes to a successful and autonomous direct candidate (a candidate who is not nominated by a party).
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This rule is designed to prevent a double influence on the composition of the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] A similar problem occurred at the federal election in 2002.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The PDS got two direct mandates in Berlin, but with only 4.0% of second votes they failed to pass the electoral threshold.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The second votes from the electors who voted for those direct candidates counted nevertheless, since in this case both candidates belonged to a party which had handed in a regional list in that Bundesland.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In its decision of November 23, 1988 (Federal Constitutional Law 79, 161), the Federal Constitutional Court pointed out the relevant loophole in the Federal Election Law to the legislative body.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Abolishing the system with first and second votes with the possibility of splitting votes – meaning the elector's option to vote for a direct candidate and for a party independently – would solve the problem automatically.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] German parliamentary election law does not have explicit abstention; a ballot paper without markings on it is considered a spoilt vote (separated into first and second vote).
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Furthermore, votes are spoilt if the voter's intention cannot be recognised without doubt, if the ballot paper contains additions or conditions or if it is not an official document.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Since the general elections in 2009, only the first vote is spoilt on ballot papers designed for a different constituency as long as they contain the correct regional list for the second vote.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The law of the German federal election does not consider ballot papers which are marked in a way that endangers the confidentiality of the ballot (as, for example, votes marked with an upright cross) as spoilt.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Invalid votes, equally to non posted votes, have no effect on the result of the poll.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Nevertheless, their number is officially counted and published.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] According to § 4 of the election statistics act, the cause of invalidity is also a census criterion to be mentioned in the official election statistics.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The numbers for a total of twelve categories of (partly) invalid ballot papers have been published at last (for the Federal Parliament elections in 2005).
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] However, it only concerns combinations of the three basic categories "empty or crossed out", "multiple crosses" and "other causes", divided into first and second votes.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Thus one can hardly deduce the reason for the invalidity; whether it was a matter of purpose, mistake or just ignorance of the voting right.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] For combinations of invalid and valid votes on a ballot paper, the belonging elected (major) parties have been deciphered as well.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Invalid votes count as non votes in the financing of the parties.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The parties do not receive any money for them.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] As the party's financing is capped and the total sum is regularly being utilised, the discrepancy of valid votes for parties who take part in financing is practically low.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] A small number of invalid votes is generally beneficial for parties with above average fund raising (membership fees included) seeing that more money remains in the bonus fund.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Seats in the German Bundestag are allocated to regional lists of parties that either pass a five percent electoral threshold of the federally valid second votes or win at least three constituencies.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The distribution of seats does not take into account second votes for parties that meet neither requirement.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Parties qualifying for proportional representation in this manner are recognized as party groups, as a party must win at least five percent of the vote to qualify as a full parliamentary party, or *Fraktion*.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Those too small to form a fraktion can make a *Gruppe* instead.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The three-constituency rule favours smaller parties with a regional stronghold.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] For example, the German Party (DP) only won 3.3% of the second vote in 1953, but was able to win 15 seats by electing ten members from constituency seats, mostly in the party's heartland of Lower Saxony.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In 1957, the DP won 3.4% of the second vote but elected six members from constituency seats, enabling them to send 17 members to the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The three-constituency rule was not used again until 1994, when the PDS won four direct mandates in Berlin, enabling them to send 30 delegates to the Bundestag, despite the fact that they had only 4.4% of the second vote.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] It was used in the 2021 election, in which PDS's successor, Die Linke, won exactly three constituencies (Berlin-Treptow-Köpenick, Berlin-Lichtenberg, and Leipzig II), earning it 39 seats on 4.9% of the second vote.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This clause is meant to minimise the risk of party fragmentation, which contributed to the incapacitation of the Reichstag in the Weimar Republic.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The clause is not explicitly mentioned in the constitution, as this could cause a conflict with the fundamental principle of equal votes (each vote must have equal weight).
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] However, the general consensus is that the clause is important for the stability of the party system, the capacity of the parliament and the government, and the overall political stability of the state.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Thus, a balance must be achieved between the two existing constitutional objectives.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The Federal Constitutional Court approves of the threshold clause, arguing that violation of a constitutional principle (within certain limits) must be permitted if it is essential to achieve a more important constitutional objective.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Therefore, the Federal Constitutional Court allows the threshold clause to be up to five percent.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Thus, the legislature has no possibility of increasing it.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] National minority parties, such as the SSW, which won a seat in the 2021 and 2025 parliamentary elections, are now freed from the electoral threshold under the constitutional imperative to protect minorities.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This special regulation however does not necessarily apply to a Turkish party, as the Turkish do not yet enjoy the status of a national minority in Germany, unlike the Danish party in Schleswig-Holstein, the SSW, or the Sorbs in Saxony.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] At first, the number of successful independent direct candidates and the successful direct candidates whose party did not make it into the German Bundestag are subtracted from the total number of 598 mandates.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In the parliamentary election of 2002, both direct candidates were members of the PDS party.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Only in the parliamentary election of 1949 were there successful independent direct candidates.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Afterwards, the obtained proportional mandates of each party are distributed among the candidates' lists of the Bundesländer, according to the number of their second votes in the respective Bundesländer, by following the same procedure.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The outcome of this procedure shows how many proportional mandates each party has gained in each Bundesland.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The candidates who have achieved a seat in the Bundestag can then be identified.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] At first, the victorious direct candidates of a party obtain their mandates in a Bundesland.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] If a party in a Bundesland receives more direct mandates than proportional mandates, all the successful candidates in constituencies gain additional seats in the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Consequently, the Bundestag becomes larger by the number of additionally gained seats.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Starting with the 2013 election, other parties receive leveling seats.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In 2017, after the formula was adjusted somewhat, there were 111 overhang and levelling seats.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In theory, there is no limit to the possible number of overhang seats; this is because one or more parties could win constituency seats while having arbitrarily few list votes.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] If a delegate of the Bundestag who was elected in a constituency in which his or her political party gained a number of excess mandates resigns, his or her seat remains free and cannot be used by the following candidate on the party's list.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] At the beginning of the 2002 legislative period the Bundestag consisted of 603 delegates.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] When SPD delegate Anke Hartnagel died and the head of SPD in Thuringia, Christoph Matschie, resigned, this regulation was enacted.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] As a consequence, the 15th Bundestag consisted of 601 members.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Debate over the awarding of overhang and leveling seats was renewed after the 2021 German federal election produced a Bundestag with 736 members, which made it the largest freely elected parliament in the world.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Instead, a party's total number of seats would be determined strictly by its share of *Zweitstimmen* (party votes), and the five-percent threshold is absolute.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] If a party wins overhang seats, the seat winners with the fewest votes would not enter the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Parties representing minority groups are still exempt from the five-percent threshold.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The law is subject to constitutional challenges by the CSU and The Left, both of whom benefit from the previous system, though President Frank-Walter Steinmeier signed the law after personally determining he believed it was constitutional.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The Bundestag, Germany's parliament, was elected according to the principle of mixed member proportional representation until the reforms of 2023 which introduced the Zweitstimmendeckung, essentially making it a party-list proportional system with a degree of localization.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Presently, the big parties are not considering introducing a majority voting system like they did at the beginning of the first grand coalition in 1966.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] However, there has been major criticism of the federal election system, as it existed prior to 2013.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The overhang seats are problematic in the sense that they distort the proportional representation (resulting from the second votes).
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The Federal Constitutional Court of Germany has found that this distinctive feature is compatible with the legislator's will of ensuring a regionally balanced composition of the Bundestag.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Nevertheless, one consequence of the overhang seats is the paradoxical possibility that a party may receive more seats in the Bundestag by receiving *fewer* second votes in certain states, or *fewer* seats if they receive *more* votes.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] On July 3, 2008, the Federal Constitutional Court declared the possibility of this so-called "negative vote weight" (*negatives Stimmgewicht*) to be unconstitutional, and reforms were implemented in May 2013 that sharply reduced this possibility.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] By the end of 1955 the CDU/CSU (political union of the parties of the Christian Democratic Union and the Christian Social Union) together with the German party (German: *Deutsche Partei (DP)*) brought forward a first draft outlining a possible majority voting system.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] According to this draft 60 percent of the mandates were supposed to be determined by majority votes and only 40 percent according to proportional representation.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Adenauer's attempt to end the CDU/CSU's dependence on the FDP (the Liberal Democratic Party) as well as to limit the SPD's (the Social Democratic Party) prospects of getting elected was unsuccessful.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] When the first Grand Coalition (1966–1969) took office, there were strong tendencies within both major parties, CDU and SPD, to abandon proportional representation which had existed/had been applied since the foundation of the German Federal Republic in 1949.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Instead, they suggested implementing the majority vote system.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] These plans were even part of the coalition agreement.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The smaller FDP, which had no chance of winning the majority in an election district, protested because the implementation of this voting system would have threatened its further existence.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Ultimately, however, the introduction of the majority vote system failed because large parts of the SPD were convinced that it would not have meant better prospects of power.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Paul Lücke (CDU), Federal Minister of the Interior, resigned from office on April 2, 1968.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Since then there have been no more attempts to introduce the majority vote system in Germany.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The paradoxes which occur with the largest remainder method are avoided by the recent introduction of the Sainte-Laguë method.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The difficulty of "negative vote weight" (where a voter's choosing to vote for a party makes it *less* likely that that party will gain seats in parliament) still remains possible.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] But German lawmakers adopted reforms in May 2013 that sharply reduce this possibility, following a July 2008 decision of the Federal Constitutional Court declaring negative vote weight unconstitutional.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The constitutional number of representatives counted 400, plus possible overhang seats and 19 Berlin representatives.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The federal territory was divided into 242 electoral districts, each one having one direct candidate being elected according to the relative majority voting, which is still valid.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] As a result of two CDU overhang seats, the Bundestag of 1949 consisted of 402 representatives.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Each German state formed its own electoral district.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Consequently, the number of representatives of a state was determined in advance (excluding overhang seats).
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Accordingly, the five-percent hurdle and the Grundmandat-clause (one direct mandate was sufficient to join the Bundestag) were valid merely in the federal states.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Using this single vote, the voter elected both a state party list and a direct candidate of the same party from his electoral district.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Therefore, the voter did not have the possibility to give separate, independent votes for the person or the direct candidate and the party or the list.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The voter of an independent direct candidate had in comparison with the two-vote system of today not the possibility to vote a party, with the risk that his vote in a case of unsuccessfulness of the candidate was lost.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In case a direct candidate resigned from the Bundestag, the corresponding electoral district had to hold a reelection.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This happened fourteen times, the first being the 1950 Kulmbach by-election.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The proportional mandates (Proporzmandate) were allocated using the D'Hondt method which disadvantages small parties.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] These parties were further disadvantaged because the seats were allocated on a per state basis.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The dual-vote system with the respective possibility of vote splitting was introduced.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In order to pass the electoral threshold, the party needed to receive a minimum of 5% of all second votes.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Although the threshold was overruled for parties of national minorities, the Südschleswigsche Landesverband (SSW) was not able to re-enter into Parliament.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The number of proportional seats increased from 400 to 484, while the 242 electoral districts were maintained.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Consequently, the Bundestag is equally represented by seats voted directly as well as via second vote, disregarding additional second vote mandates that have resulted from overhang seats.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] The number of Berlin's parliament members increased from 19 to 22.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In the case of a direct candidate withdrawing from the Bundestag, a new election in his voting district was no longer necessary.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Instead, the candidate being next in the state's list of candidates ("Landesliste") would substitute the candidate.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] In the federal states that were formerly part of Eastern Germany, including Berlin, 80 constituencies were added.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Because of this, the number of constituencies increased to 328, the number of proportional mandates to 656.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] Another consequence of German reunification was the abolition of a special regulation for West Berlin.
[src:annette-faße/electoral-system-of-germany] This regulation prescribed that the Berlin City Parliament elected 22 representatives into the Bundestag on the day of the federal election.
